The '''Chimakuan''' language family consists of one extinct and one severely endangered language spoken in northwestern [[Washington (state)|Washington state]], United States, on the [[Olympic Peninsula]]. It is part of the [[Mosan languages|Mosan]] [[sprachbund]], and one of its languages is famous for having no [[nasal stop|nasal consonants]]. The two languages were about as close as English and [[German language|German]].{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}

==Family division==
# '''[[Chemakum language|Chemakum]]''' (also known as Chimakum or Chimacum) ''(†)''
# '''[[Quileute language|Quileute]]''' (also known as Quillayute) ''(†)''

Chemakum is now [[Extinct language|extinct]]. It was spoken until the 1940s on the east side of the Olympic Peninsula between [[Port Townsend, Washington|Port Townsend]] and [[Hood Canal]]. The name Chemakum is an Anglicized version of a Salishan word for the [[Chimakum]] people, such as the nearby [[Skokomish (tribe)|Twana]] word ''čə́bqəb'' {{IPA|[t͡ʃə́bqəb]}} (earlier {{IPA|[t͡ʃə́mqəm]}}).

Quileute is now severely [[endangered language|endangered]]. It is spoken by a few people south of the [[Makah people|Makah]] on the western coast of the Olympic peninsula south of Cape Flattery at La Push and the lower [[Hoh River]]. The name Quileute comes from ''kʷoʔlí·yot''' {{IPA|[kʷoʔlíːjotʼ]}}, the name of a village at La Push.

==Phonology==
The Chimakuan languages have phonemic inventories similar to other languages of the Mosan sprachbund, with three vowels, [[ejective consonant]]s, [[uvular consonant]]s, and [[lateral affricate]]s. However, both languages have typological oddities: Chemakum had no simple [[velar consonant]]s, and Quileute has no [[nasal stop|nasal consonants]].

===Proto-Chimakuan===
The (pre-)Proto-Chimakuan sound system contained three vowels, long and short, and lexical stress. It had the following consonants.

