In Proto-Chimakuan the series {{IPA|[t͡ʃ t͡ʃʼ ʃ]}} occurred (mostly?) before the vowel {{IPA|/i/}}. On the other hand, {{IPA|[kʷ kʷʼ xʷ]}} occurred (mostly?) before the vowels {{IPA|/a, o/}}. These series may have become separate phonemes before Chimakum and Quileute split, but if so, it seems clear that they had been [[allophone]]s not long before then.

In Quileute the stress became fixed to the penultimate syllable, though subsequent changes made it somewhat unpredictable, and the glottalized sonorants became allophonic with glottal stop-sonorant sequences and so can no longer be considered phonemic. Open syllables developed long vowels. Perhaps as recently as the late 19th century, the nasals {{IPA|/m n m̰ n̰/}} became voiced plosives {{IPA|/b d ʔb ʔd/}}.

In Chemakum, stressed vowels frequently acquired glottal stops; {{IPA|/t͡ʃ t͡ʃʼ ʃ/}} depalatalized to {{IPA|/t͡s t͡sʼ s/}}, while {{IPA|/k kʼ x/}} palatalized to {{IPA|/t͡ʃ t͡ʃʼ ʃ/}}; sonorants lost their glottalization; and the approximants {{IPA|/j w j̰ w̰/}} hardened to {{IPA|/t͡ʃ kʷ/}} in the environment of stressed vowels.

